    <title type="text">New Testament Greek Vocabulary Assessment</title>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<a href="http://vocab.oxlos.com/"><span style="font-size:
      small;">New Testament Greek Vocabulary Assessment </span></a><br
      /><blockquote class="tr_bq"><div class="row"><div
      class="col-md-12"><div class="lead"><span style="font-size: x-small;">The
      eventual goal of this site is to quickly assess the vocabulary coverage of a student learning
      New Testament Greek and to better understand coverage across the lexicon at various stages in a
      student’s progression.</span><br /><span style="font-size: x-small;"><br
      /></span><span style="font-size: x-small;">The immediate goal is just to gather
      some data. So the site will just test you on your knowledge of the meaning of various nouns in
      the Greek New Testament.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;">There are no user accounts so there’s no need to sign up or anything. You can
      answer as many questions as you like and come back to this site at any time. It’s completely
      anonymous.&nbsp;</span><br /><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;">You can be an established Greek scholar or just a beginning student (in fact, I
      need a wide range of knowledge levels) but you should have learnt at least a small
      vocabulary.</span> </div></div></div></blockquote><blockquote
      class="tr_bq"><div class="row"><div class="col-md-12"><div
      class="lead"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://vocab.oxlos.com/question/">Begin
      Here</a></span></div></div></div></blockquote><div
      style="text-align: center;">And see also AWOL's&nbsp; list of</div><div
      style="text-align: center;"><a
      href="http://ancientworldonline.blogspot.com/2009/09/open-access-textbooks.html">Open Access
      Textbooks and Language Primers Relating to the Ancient World </a></div>]]></content>
